There are many airborne dust centers around the world. These centers appear after land degradation, which may relate to human activities. The most important factors in shaping dust centers are lack of water, soil salinization, low vegetation cover, and high-speed winds (
 Al-Hemoud et al., 2019; 
 Middleton, 2017). As mentioned, meteorological conditions especially precipitation and wind speed are the key to the formation of airborne dust centers. North Africa (the Great Sahara region), Pakistan, India, China, Syria, Iran, Iraq, Persian Gulf region countries, etc. Are affected by wind erosion and face the consequences of airborne dust centers (
 Manisalidis et al., 2020; 
 Middleton, 2017). Airborne dust is one of the most important causes of air pollution in the mentioned areas (
 Miri et al., 2009).
